<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-06-10T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-06-10T09:00:00-05:00" n="388" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d388">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">500.C/1013: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Tittmann</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-06-10T15:00:00+01:00">June 10,
                                    1940—3 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received 3:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>81. Avenol, Secretary General, League of Nations, has had brought to his
                            attention letter dated April 14, 1940, understood to have been published
                            June 1st, written by the President to Dr. Mary E. Woolley regarding
                            technical work of League of Nations.<note n="11" xml:id="d388fn11">S.
                                Shepard Jones and Denys P. Myers (eds.), <hi rend="italic">Documents
                                    on American Foreign Relations</hi>, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, July 1939–June 1940 (Boston, World Peace Foundation,
                                1940), p. 607.</note> Avenol would be grateful if it could be found
                            possible to convey to the President his deep appreciation for the
                            interest taken in this matter.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Tittmann</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>